# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: factor-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] In statistics, **confirmatory factor analysis** (**CFA**) is a special form of factor analysis, most commonly used in social science research.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] It is used to test whether measures of a construct are consistent with a researcher's understanding of the nature of that construct (or factor).
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] As such, the objective of confirmatory factor analysis is to test whether the data fit a hypothesized measurement model.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] This hypothesized model is based on theory and/or previous analytic research.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] CFA was first developed by Jöreskog (1969) and has built upon and replaced older methods of analyzing construct validity such as the MTMM Matrix as described in Campbell & Fiske (1959).
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] By imposing these constraints, the researcher is forcing the model to be consistent with their theory.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] For example, if it is posited that there are two factors accounting for the covariance in the measures, and that these factors are unrelated to each other, the researcher can create a model where the correlation between factor A and factor B is constrained to zero.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Model fit measures could then be obtained to assess how well the proposed model captured the covariance between all the items or measures in the model.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] If the constraints the researcher has imposed on the model are inconsistent with the sample data, then the results of statistical tests of model fit will indicate a poor fit, and the model will be rejected.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] If the fit is poor, it may be due to some items measuring multiple factors.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] It might also be that some items within a factor are more related to each other than others.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] For some applications, the requirement of "zero loadings" (for indicators not supposed to load on a certain factor) has been regarded as too strict.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] A newly developed analysis method, "exploratory structural equation modeling", specifies hypotheses about the relation between observed indicators and their supposed primary latent factors while allowing for estimation of loadings with other latent factors as well.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] In confirmatory factor analysis, researchers are typically interested in studying the degree to which responses on a *p* x 1 vector of observable random variables can be used to assign a value to one or more unobserved variable(s) *$\xi$*.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The investigation is largely accomplished by estimating and evaluating the loading of each item used to tap aspects of the unobserved latent variable.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] where Y is the *p* x 1 vector of observed random variables, $\xi$ are the unobserved latent variables and $\Lambda$ is a *p* x *k* matrix with *k* equal to the number of latent variables.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Since, Y are imperfect measures of $\xi$ , the model also consists of error, $\epsilon$ .
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] where $\Lambda \Omega \Lambda {'}+I-\operatorname {diag} (\Lambda \Omega \Lambda {'})$ is the variance-covariance matrix implied by the proposed factor analysis model and R is the observed variance-covariance matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] That is, values are found for free model parameters that minimize the difference between the model-implied variance-covariance matrix and observed variance-covariance matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Although numerous algorithms have been used to estimate CFA models, maximum likelihood (ML) remains the primary estimation procedure.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] That being said, CFA models are often applied to data conditions that deviate from the normal theory requirements for valid ML estimation.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] For example, social scientists often estimate CFA models with non-normal data and indicators scaled using discrete ordered categories.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Accordingly, alternative algorithms have been developed that attend to the diverse data conditions applied researchers encounter.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The alternative estimators have been characterized into two general type: (1) robust and (2) limited information estimator.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] When ML is implemented with data that deviates away from the assumptions of normal theory, CFA models may produce biased parameter estimates and misleading conclusions.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Robust estimation typically attempts to correct the problem by adjusting the normal theory model χ2 and standard errors.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] For example, Satorra and Bentler (1994) recommended using ML estimation in the usual way and subsequently dividing the model χ2 by a measure of the degree of multivariate kurtosis.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] An added advantage of robust ML estimators is their availability in common SEM software (e.g., LAVAAN).
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Unfortunately, robust ML estimators can become untenable under common data conditions.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] In particular, when indicators are scaled using few response categories (e.g., *disagree*, *neutral*, *agree*) robust ML estimators tend to perform poorly.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Limited information estimators, such as weighted least squares (WLS), are likely a better choice when manifest indicators take on an ordinal form.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Broadly, limited information estimators attend to the ordinal indicators by using polychoric correlations to fit CFA models.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Polychoric correlations capture the covariance between two latent variables when only their categorized form is observed, which is achieved largely through the estimation of threshold parameters.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Both **exploratory factor analysis** (EFA) and **confirmatory factor analysis** (CFA) are employed to understand shared variance of measured variables that is believed to be attributable to a factor or latent construct.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Despite this similarity, however, EFA and CFA are conceptually and statistically distinct analyses.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The goal of EFA is to identify factors based on data and to maximize the amount of variance explained.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The researcher is not required to have any specific hypotheses about how many factors will emerge, and what items or variables these factors will comprise.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] If these hypotheses exist, they are not incorporated into and do not affect the results of the statistical analyses.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] By contrast, CFA evaluates *a priori* hypotheses and is largely driven by theory.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] CFA analyses require the researcher to hypothesize, in advance, the number of factors, whether or not these factors are correlated, and which items/measures load onto and reflect which factors.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] As such, in contrast to exploratory factor analysis, where all loadings are free to vary, CFA allows for the explicit constraint of certain loadings to be zero.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] EFA is often considered to be more appropriate than CFA in the early stages of scale development because CFA does not show how well the items load on the non-hypothesized factors.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Another strong argument for the initial use of EFA is that the misspecification of the number of factors at an early stage of scale development will typically not be detected by confirmatory factor analysis.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] At later stages of scale development, confirmatory techniques may provide more information by the explicit contrast of competing factor structures.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] EFA is sometimes reported in research when CFA would be a better statistical approach.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] It has been argued that CFA can be restrictive and inappropriate when used in an exploratory fashion.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] However, the idea that CFA is solely a “confirmatory” analysis may sometimes be misleading, as modification indices used in CFA are somewhat exploratory in nature.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Modification indices show the improvement in model fit if a particular coefficient were to become unconstrained.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Likewise, EFA and CFA do not have to be mutually exclusive analyses; EFA has been argued to be a reasonable follow up to a poor-fitting CFA model.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Structural equation modeling software is typically used for performing confirmatory factor analysis.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] LISREL, EQS, AMOS, Mplus, Jamovi , and LAVAAN package in R are popular software programs.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] There is also the Python package semopy 2.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] CFA is also frequently used as a first step to assess the proposed measurement model in a structural equation model.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Many of the rules of interpretation regarding assessment of model fit and model modification in structural equation modeling apply equally to CFA.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] CFA is distinguished from structural equation modeling by the fact that in CFA, there are no directed arrows between latent factors.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] In other words, while in CFA factors are not presumed to directly cause one another, SEM often does specify particular factors and variables to be causal in nature.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] In the context of SEM, the CFA is often called 'the measurement model', while the relations between the latent variables (with directed arrows) are called 'the structural model'.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] In CFA, several statistical tests are used to determine how well the model fits to the data.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Note that a good fit between the model and the data does not mean that the model is “correct”, or even that it explains a large proportion of the covariance.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] A “good model fit” only indicates that the model is plausible.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] With regard to selecting model fit statistics to report, one should not simply report the statistics that estimate the best fit, though this may be tempting.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Though several varying opinions exist, Kline (2010) recommends reporting the chi-squared test, the root mean square error of approximation (RMSEA), the comparative fit index (CFI), and the standardised root mean square residual (SRMR).
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Absolute fit indices determine how well the a priori model fits, or reproduces the data.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Absolute fit indices include, but are not limited to, the Chi-Squared test, RMSEA, GFI, AGFI, RMR, and SRMR.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The chi-squared test indicates the difference between observed and expected covariance matrices.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Values closer to zero indicate a better fit; smaller difference between expected and observed covariance matrices.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Chi-squared statistics can also be used to directly compare the fit of nested models to the data.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] One difficulty with the chi-squared test of model fit, however, is that researchers may fail to reject an inappropriate model in small sample sizes and reject an appropriate model in large sample sizes.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] As a result, other measures of fit have been developed.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The root mean square error of approximation (RMSEA) avoids issues of sample size by analyzing the discrepancy between the hypothesized model, with optimally chosen parameter estimates, and the population covariance matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The RMSEA ranges from 0 to 1, with smaller values indicating better model fit.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] A value of .06 or less is indicative of acceptable model fit.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The root mean square residual (RMR) and standardized root mean square residual (SRMR) are the square root of the discrepancy between the sample covariance matrix and the model covariance matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The RMR may be somewhat difficult to interpret, however, as its range is based on the scales of the indicators in the model (this becomes tricky when there are multiple indicators with varying scales; e.g., two questionnaires, one on a 0–10 scale, the other on a 1–3 scale).
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The standardized root mean square residual removes this difficulty in interpretation, and ranges from 0 to 1, with a value of .08 or less being indicative of an acceptable model.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The goodness of fit index (GFI) is a measure of fit between the hypothesized model and the observed covariance matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The adjusted goodness of fit index (AGFI) corrects the GFI, which is affected by the number of indicators of each latent variable.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The GFI and AGFI range between 0 and 1, with a value of over .9 generally indicating acceptable model fit.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Relative fit indices (also called “incremental fit indices” and “comparative fit indices”) compare the chi-square for the hypothesized model to one from a “null”, or “baseline” model.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] This null model almost always contains a model in which all of the variables are uncorrelated, and as a result, has a very large chi-square (indicating poor fit).
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Relative fit indices include the normed fit index and comparative fit index.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The normed fit index (NFI) analyzes the discrepancy between the chi-squared value of the hypothesized model and the chi-squared value of the null model.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] However, NFI tends to be negatively biased.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The non-normed fit index (NNFI; also known as the Tucker–Lewis index, as it was built on an index formed by Tucker and Lewis, in 1973) resolves some of the issues of negative bias, though NNFI values may sometimes fall beyond the 0 to 1 range.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Values for both the NFI and NNFI should range between 0 and 1, with a cutoff of .95 or greater indicating a good model fit.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] The comparative fit index (CFI) analyzes the model fit by examining the discrepancy between the data and the hypothesized model, while adjusting for the issues of sample size inherent in the chi-squared test of model fit, and the normed fit index.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] CFI values range from 0 to 1, with larger values indicating better fit.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Previously, a CFI value of .90 or larger was considered to indicate acceptable model fit.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] However, a 1999 study indicated that a value greater than .90 is needed to ensure that misspecified models are not deemed acceptable.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] Thus, a CFI value of .95 or higher is presently accepted as an indicator of good fit.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] To estimate the parameters of a model, the model must be properly identified.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] That is, the number of estimated (unknown) parameters (*q*) must be less than or equal to the number of unique variances and covariances among the measured variables; *p*(*p* + 1)/2.
[src:factor-analysis/confirmatory-factor-analysis] If there is too little information available on which to base the parameter estimates, then the model is said to be underidentified, and model parameters cannot be estimated appropriately.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] In multivariate statistics, **exploratory factor analysis** (**EFA**) is a statistical method used to uncover the underlying structure of a relatively large set of variables.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] EFA is a technique within factor analysis whose overarching goal is to identify the underlying relationships between measured variables.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] It is commonly used by researchers when developing a scale (a *scale* is a collection of questions used to measure a particular research topic) and serves to identify a set of latent constructs underlying a battery of measured variables.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] It should be used when the researcher has no *a priori* hypothesis about factors or patterns of measured variables.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] *Measured variables* are any one of several attributes of people that may be observed and measured.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Examples of measured variables could be the physical height, weight, and pulse rate of a human being.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Usually, researchers would have a large number of measured variables, which are assumed to be related to a smaller number of "unobserved" factors.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Researchers must carefully consider the number of measured variables to include in the analysis.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] EFA procedures are more accurate when each factor is represented by multiple measured variables in the analysis.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] EFA is based on the common factor model.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] In this model, manifest variables are expressed as a function of common factors, unique factors, and errors of measurement.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Each unique factor influences only one manifest variable, and does not explain correlations between manifest variables.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Common factors influence more than one manifest variable and "factor loadings" are measures of the influence of a common factor on a manifest variable.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] For the EFA procedure, we are more interested in identifying the common factors and the related manifest variables.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] EFA assumes that any indicator/measured variable may be associated with any factor.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] When developing a scale, researchers should use EFA first before moving on to confirmatory factor analysis.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] EFA is essential to determine underlying factors/constructs for a set of measured variables; while confirmatory factor analysis allows the researcher to test the hypothesis that a relationship between the observed variables and their underlying latent factor(s)/construct(s) exists.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] EFA requires the researcher to make a number of important decisions about how to conduct the analysis because there is no one set method.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Fitting procedures are used to estimate the factor loadings and unique variances of the model (*Factor loadings* are the regression coefficients between items and factors and measure the influence of a common factor on a measured variable).
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] There are several factor analysis fitting methods to choose from, however there is little information on all of their strengths and weaknesses and many don't even have an exact name that is used consistently.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Principal axis factoring (PAF) and maximum likelihood (ML) are two extraction methods that are generally recommended.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] In general, ML or PAF give the best results, depending on whether data are normally-distributed or if the assumption of normality has been violated.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Called “principal” axis factoring because the first factor accounts for as much common variance as possible, then the second factor next most variance, and so on.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] PAF is a descriptive procedure so it is best to use when the focus is just on your sample and you do not plan to generalize the results beyond your sample.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] A downside of PAF is that it provides a limited range of goodness-of-fit indexes compared to ML and does not allow for the computation of confidence intervals and significance tests.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] When selecting how many factors to include in a model, researchers must try to balance parsimony (a model with relatively few factors) and plausibility (that there are enough factors to adequately account for correlations among measured variables).
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] There are a number of procedures designed to determine the optimal number of factors to retain in EFA.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Broadly speaking, most of the existing procedures approach the determination of the appropriate number of factors (1) by inspecting patterns of eigenvalues of the covariance matrix, or (2) treating it as a model selection problem.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Recent simulation studies assessing the robustness of such techniques suggest that the latter five can better assist practitioners to judiciously model data.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] These five modern techniques are now easily accessible through integrated use of IBM SPSS Statistics software (SPSS) and R (R Development Core Team, 2011).
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] See Courtney (2013) for guidance on how to carry out these procedures for continuous, ordinal, and heterogenous (continuous and ordinal) data.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] With the exception of Revelle and Rocklin's (1979) very simple structure criterion, model comparison techniques, and Velicer's (1976) minimum average partial, all other procedures rely on the analysis of eigenvalues.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The *eigenvalue* of a factor represents the amount of variance of the variables accounted for by that factor.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The lower the eigenvalue, the less that factor contributes to explaining the variance of the variables.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] A short description of each of the nine procedures mentioned above is provided below.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Kaiser's criterion, named after the American psychologist Henry Felix Kaiser, determines the number of factors by compute the eigenvalues for the correlation matrix and counting how many of these eigenvalues are greater than 1.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] This number is the number of factors to include in the model.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] A disadvantage of this procedure is that it is quite arbitrary (e.g., an eigenvalue of 1.01 is included whereas an eigenvalue of .99 is not).
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] This procedure often leads to overfactoring, and sometimes underfactoring, and is widely regarded as suboptimal in comparison to more modern methods.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] A variation of the K1 criterion has been created to lessen the severity of the criterion's problems where a researcher calculates confidence intervals for each eigenvalue and retains only factors which have the entire confidence interval greater than 1.0.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Compute the eigenvalues for the correlation matrix and plot the values from largest to smallest.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Examine the graph to determine the last substantial drop in the magnitude of eigenvalues.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The number of plotted points before the last drop is the number of factors to include in the model.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] This method has been criticized because of its subjective nature (i.e., there is no clear objective definition of what constitutes a substantial drop).
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] As this procedure is subjective, Courtney (2013) does not recommend it.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Revelle and Rocklin's (1979) VSS criterion operationalizes this tendency by assessing the extent to which the original correlation matrix is reproduced by a simplified pattern matrix, in which only the highest loading for each item is retained, all other loadings being set to zero.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The VSS criterion for assessing the extent of replication can take values between 0 and 1, and is a measure of the goodness-of-fit of the factor solution.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The VSS criterion is gathered from factor solutions that involve one factor (k = 1) to a user-specified theoretical maximum number of factors.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Thereafter, the factor solution that provides the highest VSS criterion determines the optimal number of interpretable factors in the matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] In an attempt to accommodate datasets where items covary with more than one factor (i.e., more factorially complex data), the criterion can also be carried out with simplified pattern matrices in which the highest two loadings are retained, with the rest set to zero (Max VSS complexity 2).
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Courtney also does not recommend VSS because of lack of robust simulation research concerning the performance of the VSS criterion.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Choose the best model from a series of models that differ in complexity.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Researchers use goodness-of-fit measures to fit models beginning with a model with zero factors and gradually increase the number of factors.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The goal is to ultimately choose a model that explains the data significantly better than simpler models (with fewer factors) and explains the data as well as more complex models (with more factors).
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] In an attempt to overcome the subjective weakness of Cattell's (1966) scree test, presented two families of non-graphical solutions.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The first method, coined the optimal coordinate (OC), attempts to determine the location of the scree by measuring the gradients associated with eigenvalues and their preceding coordinates.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The second method, coined the acceleration factor (AF), pertains to a numerical solution for determining the coordinate where the slope of the curve changes most abruptly.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Both of these methods have out-performed the K1 method in simulation.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] In the Ruscio and Roche study (2012), the OC method was correct 74.03% of the time rivaling the PA technique (76.42%).
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The AF method was correct 45.91% of the time with a tendency toward under-estimation.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Both the OC and AF methods, generated with the use of Pearson correlation coefficients, were reviewed in Ruscio and Roche's (2012) simulation study.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Results suggested that both techniques performed quite well under ordinal response categories of two to seven (C = 2-7) and quasi-continuous (C = 10 or 20) data situations.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Given the accuracy of these procedures under simulation, they are highly recommended for determining the number of factors to retain in EFA.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] It is one of Courtney's 5 recommended modern procedures.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Velicer's (1976) MAP test “involves a complete principal components analysis followed by the examination of a series of matrices of partial correlations” (p.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The squared correlation for Step “0” (see Figure 4) is the average squared off-diagonal correlation for the unpartialed correlation matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] On Step 1, the first principal component and its associated items are partialed out.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Thereafter, the average squared off-diagonal correlation for the subsequent correlation matrix is computed for Step 1.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] On Step 2, the first two principal components are partialed out and the resultant average squared off-diagonal correlation is again computed.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The computations are carried out for k minus one steps (k representing the total number of variables in the matrix).
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Finally, the average squared correlations for all steps are lined up and the step number that resulted in the lowest average squared partial correlation determines the number of components or factors to retain (Velicer, 1976).
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] By this method, components are maintained as long as the variance in the correlation matrix represents systematic variance, as opposed to residual or error variance.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Although methodologically akin to principal components analysis, the MAP technique has been shown to perform quite well in determining the number of factors to retain in multiple simulation studies.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] However, in a very small minority of cases MAP may grossly overestimate the number of factors in a dataset for unknown reasons.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] This procedure is made available through SPSS's user interface.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] This is one of his five recommended modern procedures.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] To carry out the PA test, users compute the eigenvalues for the correlation matrix and plot the values from largest to smallest and then plot a set of random eigenvalues.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The number of eigenvalues before the intersection points indicates how many factors to include in your model.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] This procedure can be somewhat arbitrary (i.e. a factor just meeting the cutoff will be included and one just below will not).
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Moreover, the method is very sensitive to sample size, with PA suggesting more factors in datasets with larger sample sizes.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Despite its shortcomings, this procedure performs very well in simulation studies and is one of Courtney's recommended procedures.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] PA has been implemented in a number of commonly used statistics programs such as R and SPSS.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] In 2012 Ruscio and Roche introduced the comparative data (CD) procedure in an attempt improve to upon the PA method.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The authors state that "rather than generating random datasets, which only take into account sampling error, multiple datasets with known factorial structures are analyzed to determine which best reproduces the profile of eigenvalues for the actual data" (p.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The strength of the procedure is its ability to not only incorporate sampling error, but also the factorial structure and multivariate distribution of the items.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Ruscio and Roche's (2012) simulation study determined that the CD procedure outperformed many other methods aimed at determining the correct number of factors to retain.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] In that study, the CD technique, making use of Pearson correlations accurately predicted the correct number of factors 87.14% of the time.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] However, the simulated study never involved more than five factors.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Therefore, the applicability of the CD procedure to estimate factorial structures beyond five factors is yet to be tested.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Courtney includes this procedure in his recommended list and gives guidelines showing how it can be easily carried out from within SPSS's user interface.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] In 2023, Goretzko and Ruscio proposed the Comparison Data Forest as an extension of the CD approach.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] A review of 60 journal articles by Henson and Roberts (2006) found that none used multiple modern techniques in an attempt to find convergence, such as PA and Velicer's (1976) minimum average partial (MAP) procedures.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Ruscio and Roche (2012) simulation study demonstrated the empirical advantage of seeking convergence.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] When the CD and PA procedures agreed, the accuracy of the estimated number of factors was correct 92.2% of the time.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Ruscio and Roche (2012) demonstrated that when further tests were in agreement, the accuracy of the estimation could be increased even further.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Recent simulation studies in the field of psychometrics suggest that the parallel analysis, minimum average partial, and comparative data techniques can be improved for different data situations.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] For example, in simulation studies, the performance of the minimum average partial test, when ordinal data is concerned, can be improved by utilizing polychoric correlations, as opposed to Pearson correlations.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Courtney (2013) details how each of these three procedures can be optimized and carried out simultaneously from within the SPSS interface.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Factor rotation is a commonly employed step in EFA, used to aide interpretation of factor matrixes.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] For any solution with two or more factors there are an infinite number of orientations of the factors that will explain the data equally well.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Because there is no unique solution, a researcher must select a single solution from the infinite possibilities.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] There are two main types of factor rotation: orthogonal and oblique rotation.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Orthogonal rotations constrain factors to be perpendicular to each other and hence uncorrelated.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] An advantage of orthogonal rotation is its simplicity and conceptual clarity, although there are several disadvantages.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] In the social sciences, there is often a theoretical basis for expecting constructs to be correlated, therefore orthogonal rotations may not be very realistic because they do not allow this.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Also, because orthogonal rotations require factors to be uncorrelated, they are less likely to produce solutions with simple structure.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Varimax rotation is an orthogonal rotation of the factor axes to maximize the variance of the squared loadings of a factor (column) on all the variables (rows) in a factor matrix, which has the effect of differentiating the original variables by extracted factor.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Each factor will tend to have either large or small loadings of any particular variable.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] A varimax solution yields results which make it as easy as possible to identify each variable with a single factor.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] This is the most common orthogonal rotation option.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Quartimax rotation is an orthogonal rotation that maximizes the squared loadings for each variable rather than each factor.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] This minimizes the number of factors needed to explain each variable.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] This type of rotation often generates a general factor on which most variables are loaded to a high or medium degree.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Equimax rotation is a compromise between varimax and quartimax criteria.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Oblique rotations permit correlations among factors.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] An advantage of oblique rotation is that it produces solutions with better simple structure when factors are expected to correlate, and it produces estimates of correlations among factors.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] These rotations may produce solutions similar to orthogonal rotation if the factors do not correlate with each other.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Several oblique rotation procedures are commonly used.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Direct oblimin rotation is the standard oblique rotation method.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Promax rotation is often seen in older literature because it is easier to calculate than oblimin.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Other oblique methods include direct quartimin rotation and Harris-Kaiser orthoblique rotation.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Common factor analysis software is capable of producing an unrotated solution.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] This refers to the result of a principal axis factoring with no further rotation.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The so-called unrotated solution is in fact an orthogonal rotation that maximizes the variance of the first factors.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The unrotated solution tends to give a general factor with loadings for most of the variables.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] This may be useful if many variables are correlated with each other, as revealed by one or a few dominating eigenvalues on a scree plot.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] The usefulness of an unrotated solution was emphasized by a meta analysis of studies of cultural differences.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] This revealed that many published studies of cultural differences have given similar factor analysis results, but rotated differently.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Factor rotation has obscured the similarity between the results of different studies and the existence of a strong general factor, while the unrotated solutions were much more similar.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Factor loadings are numerical values that indicate the strength and direction of a factor on a measured variable.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Factor loadings indicate how strongly the factor influences the measured variable.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] In order to label the factors in the model, researchers should examine the factor pattern to see which items load highly on which factors and then determine what those items have in common.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Whatever the items have in common will indicate the meaning of the factor.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Interpretation has long been noted as an important, but difficult, part of the analytic process.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] However, while exploratory factor analysis is a powerful tool for uncovering underlying structures among variables, it is crucial to avoid reliance on it without adequate theorizing.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Armstrong's critique highlights that EFA, when conducted without a theoretical framework, can lead to misleading interpretations.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] For instance, in a hypothetical case study involving the analysis of various physical properties of metals, the results of EFA failed to identify the true underlying factors, instead producing an "over-factored" model that obscured the simplicity of the relationships amongst the observed variables.
[src:factor-analysis/exploratory-factor-analysis] Similarly, poorly designed survey items can lead to spurious factor structures.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The correlation between a variable and a given factor, called the variable's factor loading, indicates the extent to which the two are related.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] A common rationale behind factor analytic methods is that the information gained about the interdependencies between observed variables can be used later to reduce the set of variables in a dataset.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis is commonly used in psychometrics, personality psychology, biology, marketing, product management, operations research, finance, and machine learning.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] It may help to deal with data sets where there are large numbers of observed variables that are thought to reflect a smaller number of underlying/latent variables.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] It is one of the most commonly used inter-dependency techniques and is used when the relevant set of variables shows a systematic inter-dependence and the objective is to find out the latent factors that create a commonality.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The model attempts to explain a set of p observations in each of n individuals with a set of k *common factors* ( $f_{i,j}$ ) where there are fewer factors per unit than observations per unit ( $k<p$ ).
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] 3. $\mathrm {Cov} (F)=I$ where $\mathrm {Cov}$ is the covariance matrix, to make sure that the factors are uncorrelated, and I is the identity matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] For any orthogonal matrix Q , if we set $L^{\prime }=\ LQ$ and $F^{\prime }=Q^{T}F$ , the criteria for being factors and factor loadings still hold.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Hence a set of factors and factor loadings is unique only up to an orthogonal transformation.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Suppose a psychologist has the hypothesis that there are two kinds of intelligence, "verbal intelligence" and "mathematical intelligence", neither of which is directly observed.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Evidence for the hypothesis is sought in the examination scores from each of 10 different academic fields of 1000 students.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] If each student is chosen randomly from a large population, then each student's 10 scores are random variables.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The numbers for a particular subject, by which the two kinds of intelligence are multiplied to obtain the expected score, are posited by the hypothesis to be the same for all intelligence level pairs, and are called **"factor loading"** for this subject.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] {10 × the student's verbal intelligence} + {6 × the student's mathematical intelligence}.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The numbers 10 and 6 are the factor loadings associated with astronomy.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Other academic subjects may have different factor loadings.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Two students assumed to have identical degrees of verbal and mathematical intelligence may have different measured aptitudes in astronomy because individual aptitudes differ from average aptitudes (predicted above) and because of measurement error itself.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Such differences make up what is collectively called the "error" — a statistical term that means the amount by which an individual, as measured, differs from what is average for or predicted by his or her levels of intelligence (see errors and residuals in statistics).
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The observable data that go into factor analysis would be 10 scores of each of the 1000 students, a total of 10,000 numbers.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The factor loadings and levels of the two kinds of intelligence of each student must be inferred from the data.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In the following, matrices will be indicated by indexed variables.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] "Academic Subject" indices will be indicated using letters a , b and c , with values running from 1 to p which is equal to $10$ in the above example.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] "Factor" indices will be indicated using letters p , q and r , with values running from 1 to k which is equal to 2 in the above example.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] "Instance" or "sample" indices will be indicated using letters i , j and k , with values running from 1 to N .
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In the example above, if a sample of $N=1000$ students participated in the $p=10$ exams, the i th student's score for the a th exam is given by $x_{ai}$ .
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The purpose of factor analysis is to characterize the correlations between the variables $x_{a}$ of which the $x_{ai}$ are a particular instance, or set of observations.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Observe that by doubling the scale on which "verbal intelligence"—the first component in each column of F —is measured, and simultaneously halving the factor loadings for verbal intelligence makes no difference to the model.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Thus, no generality is lost by assuming that the standard deviation of the factors for verbal intelligence is 1 .
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Moreover, for similar reasons, no generality is lost by assuming the two factors are uncorrelated with each other.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] where $\delta _{pq}$ is the Kronecker delta ( 0 when $p\neq q$ and 1 when $p=q$ ).
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Since any rotation of a solution is also a solution, this makes interpreting the factors difficult.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In this particular example, if we do not know beforehand that the two types of intelligence are uncorrelated, then we cannot interpret the two factors as the two different types of intelligence.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Even if they are uncorrelated, we cannot tell which factor corresponds to verbal intelligence and which corresponds to mathematical intelligence without an outside argument.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The values of the loadings L , the averages $\mu$ , and the variances of the "errors" $\varepsilon$ must be estimated given the observed data X and F (the assumption about the levels of the factors is fixed for a given F ).
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The term on the left is the $(a,b)$ -term of the correlation matrix (a $p\times p$ matrix derived as the product of the $p\times N$ matrix of standardized observations with its transpose) of the observed data, and its p diagonal elements will be 1 s.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The second term on the right will be a diagonal matrix with terms less than unity.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The first term on the right is the "reduced correlation matrix" and will be equal to the correlation matrix except for its diagonal values which will be less than unity.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The sample data $z_{ai}$ will not exactly obey the fundamental equation given above due to sampling errors, inadequacy of the model, etc.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The goal of any analysis of the above model is to find the factors $F_{pi}$ and loadings $\ell _{ap}$ which give a "best fit" to the data.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] This is equivalent to minimizing the off-diagonal components of the error covariance which, in the model equations have expected values of zero.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] This is to be contrasted with principal component analysis which seeks to minimize the mean square error of all residuals.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Before the advent of high-speed computers, considerable effort was devoted to finding approximate solutions to the problem, particularly in estimating the communalities by other means, which then simplifies the problem considerably by yielding a known reduced correlation matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] This was then used to estimate the factors and the loadings.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] With the advent of high-speed computers, the minimization problem can be solved iteratively with adequate speed, and the communalities are calculated in the process, rather than being needed beforehand.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The MinRes algorithm is particularly suited to this problem, but is hardly the only iterative means of finding a solution.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] If the solution factors are allowed to be correlated (as in 'oblimin' rotation, for example), then the corresponding mathematical model uses skew coordinates rather than orthogonal coordinates.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The parameters and variables of factor analysis can be given a geometrical interpretation.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The data ( $z_{ai}$ ), the factors ( $F_{pi}$ ) and the errors ( $\varepsilon _{ai}$ ) can be viewed as vectors in an N -dimensional Euclidean space (sample space), represented as $\mathbf {z} _{a}$ , $\mathbf {F} _{p}$ and ${\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}_{a}$ respectively.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Since the data are standardized, the data vectors are of unit length ( $||\mathbf {z} _{a}||=1$ ).
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The factor vectors define a k -dimensional linear subspace (i.e. a hyperplane) in this space, upon which the data vectors are projected orthogonally.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] and the independence of the factors and the errors: $\mathbf {F} _{p}\cdot {\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}_{a}=0$ .
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In the above example, the hyperplane is just a 2-dimensional plane defined by the two factor vectors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] and the errors are vectors from that projected point to the data point and are perpendicular to the hyperplane.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The goal of factor analysis is to find a hyperplane which is a "best fit" to the data in some sense, so it doesn't matter how the factor vectors which define this hyperplane are chosen, as long as they are independent and lie in the hyperplane.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] We are free to specify them as both orthogonal and normal ( $\mathbf {F} _{p}\cdot \mathbf {F} _{q}=\delta _{pq}$ ) with no loss of generality.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] After a suitable set of factors are found, they may also be arbitrarily rotated within the hyperplane, so that any rotation of the factor vectors will define the same hyperplane, and also be a solution.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] As a result, in the above example, in which the fitting hyperplane is two dimensional, if we do not know beforehand that the two types of intelligence are uncorrelated, then we cannot interpret the two factors as the two different types of intelligence.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Even if they are uncorrelated, we cannot tell which factor corresponds to verbal intelligence and which corresponds to mathematical intelligence, or whether the factors are linear combinations of both, without an outside argument.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The data vectors $\mathbf {z} _{a}$ have unit length.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The entries of the correlation matrix for the data are given by $r_{ab}=\mathbf {z} _{a}\cdot \mathbf {z} _{b}$ .
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The correlation matrix can be geometrically interpreted as the cosine of the angle between the two data vectors $\mathbf {z} _{a}$ and $\mathbf {z} _{b}$ .
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The diagonal elements will clearly be 1 s and the off diagonal elements will have absolute values less than or equal to unity.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The goal of factor analysis is to choose the fitting hyperplane such that the reduced correlation matrix reproduces the correlation matrix as nearly as possible, except for the diagonal elements of the correlation matrix which are known to have unit value.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In other words, the goal is to reproduce as accurately as possible the cross-correlations in the data.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] is to be minimized, and this is accomplished by minimizing it with respect to a set of orthonormal factor vectors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The term on the right is just the covariance of the errors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In the model, the error covariance is stated to be a diagonal matrix and so the above minimization problem will in fact yield a "best fit" to the model: It will yield a sample estimate of the error covariance which has its off-diagonal components minimized in the mean square sense.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] It can be seen that since the ${\hat {z}}_{a}$ are orthogonal projections of the data vectors, their length will be less than or equal to the length of the projected data vector, which is unity.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The square of these lengths are just the diagonal elements of the reduced correlation matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Large values of the communalities will indicate that the fitting hyperplane is rather accurately reproducing the correlation matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The mean values of the factors must also be constrained to be zero, from which it follows that the mean values of the errors will also be zero.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Exploratory factor analysis (EFA) is used to identify complex interrelationships among items and group items that are part of unified concepts.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The researcher makes no *a priori* assumptions about relationships among factors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Confirmatory factor analysis (CFA) is a more complex approach that tests the hypothesis that the items are associated with specific factors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] CFA uses structural equation modeling to test a measurement model whereby loading on the factors allows for evaluation of relationships between observed variables and unobserved variables.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Structural equation modeling approaches can accommodate measurement error and are less restrictive than least-squares estimation.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Hypothesized models are tested against actual data, and the analysis would demonstrate loadings of observed variables on the latent variables (factors), as well as the correlation between the latent variables.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Principal component analysis (PCA) is a widely used method for factor extraction, which is the first phase of EFA.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor weights are computed to extract the maximum possible variance, with successive factoring continuing until there is no further meaningful variance left.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The factor model must then be rotated for analysis.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Canonical factor analysis, also called Rao's canonical factoring, is a different method of computing the same model as PCA, which uses the principal axis method.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Canonical factor analysis seeks factors that have the highest canonical correlation with the observed variables.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Canonical factor analysis is unaffected by arbitrary rescaling of the data.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Common factor analysis, also called principal factor analysis (PFA) or principal axis factoring (PAF), seeks the fewest factors which can account for the common variance (correlation) of a set of variables.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Image factoring is based on the correlation matrix of predicted variables rather than actual variables, where each variable is predicted from the others using multiple regression.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Alpha factoring is based on maximizing the reliability of factors, assuming variables are randomly sampled from a universe of variables.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] All other methods assume cases to be sampled and variables fixed.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor regression model is a combinatorial model of factor model and regression model; or alternatively, it can be viewed as the hybrid factor model, whose factors are partially known.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Communality is the square of the standardized outer loading of an item.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] However, the .7 standard is a high one and real-life data may well not meet this criterion, which is why some researchers, particularly for exploratory purposes, will use a lower level such as .4 for the central factor and .25 for other factors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In any event, factor loadings must be interpreted in the light of theory, not by arbitrary cutoff levels.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] rotation, one may examine both a pattern matrix and a structure matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The structure matrix is simply the factor loading matrix as in orthogonal rotation, representing the variance in a measured variable explained by a factor on both a unique and common contributions basis.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] which just represent unique contributions.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The more factors, the lower the pattern coefficients as a rule since there will be more common contributions to variance explained.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] For oblique rotation, the researcher looks at both the structure and pattern coefficients when attributing a label to a factor.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Principles of oblique rotation can be derived from both cross entropy and its dual entropy.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The sum of the squared factor loadings for all factors for a given variable (row) is the variance in that variable accounted for by all the factors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The communality measures the percent of variance in a given variable explained by all the factors jointly and may be interpreted as the reliability of the indicator in the context of the factors being posited.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] If the communality exceeds 1.0, there is a spurious solution, which may reflect too small a sample or the choice to extract too many or too few factors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The variability of a variable minus its communality.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Eigenvalues measure the amount of variation in the total sample accounted for by each factor.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The ratio of eigenvalues is the ratio of explanatory importance of the factors with respect to the variables.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] If a factor has a low eigenvalue, then it is contributing little to the explanation of variances in the variables and may be ignored as less important than the factors with higher eigenvalues.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Initial eigenvalues and eigenvalues after extraction (listed by SPSS as "Extraction Sums of Squared Loadings") are the same for PCA extraction, but for other extraction methods, eigenvalues after extraction will be lower than their initial counterparts.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] SPSS also prints "Rotation Sums of Squared Loadings" and even for PCA, these eigenvalues will differ from initial and extraction eigenvalues, though their total will be the same.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The scores of each case (row) on each factor (column).
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] To compute the factor score for a given case for a given factor, one takes the case's standardized score on each variable, multiplies by the corresponding loadings of the variable for the given factor, and sums these products.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Computing factor scores allows one to look for factor outliers.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Also, factor scores may be used as variables in subsequent modeling.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Researchers wish to avoid such subjective or arbitrary criteria for factor retention as "it made sense to me".
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] A number of objective methods have been developed to solve this problem, allowing users to determine an appropriate range of solutions to investigate.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] However these different methods often disagree with one another as to the number of factors that ought to be retained.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] For instance, the parallel analysis may suggest 5 factors while Velicer's MAP suggests 6, so the researcher may request both 5 and 6-factor solutions and discuss each in terms of their relation to external data and theory.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Horn's parallel analysis (PA): A Monte-Carlo based simulation method that compares the observed eigenvalues with those obtained from uncorrelated normal variables.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] A factor or component is retained if the associated eigenvalue is bigger than the 95th percentile of the distribution of eigenvalues derived from the random data.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] PA is among the more commonly recommended rules for determining the number of components to retain, but many programs fail to include this option (a notable exception being R).
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] However, Formann provided both theoretical and empirical evidence that its application might not be appropriate in many cases since its performance is considerably influenced by sample size, item discrimination, and type of correlation coefficient.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Velicer's (1976) MAP test as described by Courtney (2013) “involves a complete principal components analysis followed by the examination of a series of matrices of partial correlations” (p.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] 397 (though this quote does not occur in Velicer (1976) and the cited page number is outside the pages of the citation).
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Thereafter, the average squared off-diagonal correlation for the subsequent correlation matrix is then computed for Step 1.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The computations are carried out for k minus one step (k representing the total number of variables in the matrix).
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Thereafter, all of the average squared correlations for each step are lined up and the step number in the analyses that resulted in the lowest average squared partial correlation determines the number of components or factors to retain.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] This procedure is made available through SPSS's user interface, as well as the *psych* package for the R programming language.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Kaiser criterion: The Kaiser rule is to drop all components with eigenvalues under 1.0 – this being the eigenvalue equal to the information accounted for by an average single item.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The Kaiser criterion is the default in SPSS and most statistical software but is not recommended when used as the sole cut-off criterion for estimating the number of factors as it tends to over-extract factors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] A variation of this method has been created where a researcher calculates confidence intervals for each eigenvalue and retains only factors which have the entire confidence interval greater than 1.0.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Scree plot: The Cattell scree test plots the components as the X-axis and the corresponding eigenvalues as the Y-axis.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] As one moves to the right, toward later components, the eigenvalues drop.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] When the drop ceases and the curve makes an elbow toward less steep decline, Cattell's scree test says to drop all further components after the one starting at the elbow.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] This rule is sometimes criticised for being amenable to researcher-controlled "fudging".
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] That is, as picking the "elbow" can be subjective because the curve has multiple elbows or is a smooth curve, the researcher may be tempted to set the cut-off at the number of factors desired by their research agenda.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Variance explained criteria: Some researchers simply use the rule of keeping enough factors to account for 90% (sometimes 80%) of the variation.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Where the researcher's goal emphasizes parsimony (explaining variance with as few factors as possible), the criterion could be as low as 50%.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] By placing a prior distribution over the number of latent factors and then applying Bayes' theorem, Bayesian models can return a probability distribution over the number of latent factors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] This has been modeled using the Indian buffet process, but can be modeled more simply by placing any discrete prior (e.g. a negative binomial distribution) on the number of components.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The output of PCA maximizes the variance accounted for by the first factor first, then the second factor, etc.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] A disadvantage of this procedure is that most items load on the early factors, while very few items load on later variables.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] This makes interpreting the factors by reading through a list of questions and loadings difficult, as every question is strongly correlated with the first few components, while very few questions are strongly correlated with the last few components.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Rotation serves to make the output easier to interpret.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] By choosing a different basis for the same principal components – that is, choosing different factors to express the same correlation structure – it is possible to create variables that are more easily interpretable.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Rotations can be orthogonal or oblique; oblique rotations allow the factors to correlate.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] This increased flexibility means that more rotations are possible, some of which may be better at achieving a specified goal.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] However, this can also make the factors more difficult to interpret, as some information is "double-counted" and included multiple times in different components; some factors may even appear to be near-duplicates of each other.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Two broad classes of orthogonal rotations exist: those that look for sparse rows (where each row is a case, i.e. subject), and those that look for sparse columns (where each column is a variable).
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] It can be difficult to interpret a factor structure when each variable is loading on multiple factors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Small changes in the data can sometimes tip a balance in the factor rotation criterion so that a completely different factor rotation is produced.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] This can make it difficult to compare the results of different experiments.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] This problem is illustrated by a comparison of different studies of world-wide cultural differences.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Each study has used different measures of cultural variables and produced a differently rotated factor analysis result.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The authors of each study believed that they had discovered something new, and invented new names for the factors they found.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] A later comparison of the studies found that the results were rather similar when the unrotated results were compared.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The common practice of factor rotation has obscured the similarity between the results of the different studies.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis is related to principal component analysis (PCA), but the two are not identical.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] There has been significant controversy in the field over differences between the two techniques.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] PCA can be considered as a more basic version of exploratory factor analysis (EFA) that was developed in the early days prior to the advent of high-speed computers.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Both PCA and factor analysis aim to reduce the dimensionality of a set of data, but the approaches taken to do so are different for the two techniques.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis is clearly designed with the objective of identifying certain unobservable factors from the observed variables, whereas PCA does not directly address this objective; at best, PCA provides an approximation to the required factors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] From the point of view of exploratory analysis, the eigenvalues of PCA are inflated component loadings, i.e., contaminated with error variance.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Whilst EFA and PCA are treated as synonymous techniques in some fields of statistics, this has been criticised.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis "deals with *the assumption of an underlying causal structure*: [it] assumes that the covariation in the observed variables is due to the presence of one or more latent variables (factors) that exert causal influence on these observed variables".
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In contrast, PCA neither assumes nor depends on such an underlying causal relationship.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Researchers have argued that the distinctions between the two techniques may mean that there are objective benefits for preferring one over the other based on the analytic goal.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] If the factor model is incorrectly formulated or the assumptions are not met, then factor analysis will give erroneous results.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis has been used successfully where adequate understanding of the system permits good initial model formulations.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] PCA employs a mathematical transformation to the original data with no assumptions about the form of the covariance matrix.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The objective of PCA is to determine linear combinations of the original variables and select a few that can be used to summarize the data set without losing much information.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] PCA and factor analysis can produce similar results.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] This point is also addressed by Fabrigar et al.; in certain cases, whereby the communalities are low (e.g.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] 0.4), the two techniques produce divergent results.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In fact, Fabrigar et al. argue that in cases where the data correspond to assumptions of the common factor model, the results of PCA are inaccurate results.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] There are certain cases where factor analysis leads to 'Heywood cases'.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] These encompass situations whereby 100% or more of the variance in a measured variable is estimated to be accounted for by the model.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Fabrigar et al. suggest that these cases are actually informative to the researcher, indicating an incorrectly specified model or a violation of the common factor model.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The lack of Heywood cases in the PCA approach may mean that such issues pass unnoticed.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Researchers gain extra information from a PCA approach, such as an individual's score on a certain component; such information is not yielded from factor analysis.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] However, as Fabrigar et al. contend, the typical aim of factor analysis – i.e. to determine the factors accounting for the structure of the correlations between measured variables – does not require knowledge of factor scores and thus this advantage is negated.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] It is also possible to compute factor scores from a factor analysis.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis takes into account the random error that is inherent in measurement, whereas PCA fails to do so.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] For this reason, Brown (2009) recommends using factor analysis when theoretical ideas about relationships between variables exist, whereas PCA should be used if the goal of the researcher is to explore patterns in their data.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Charles Spearman was the first psychologist to discuss common factor analysis and did so in his 1904 paper.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] It provided few details about his methods and was concerned with single-factor models.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] He discovered that school children's scores on a wide variety of seemingly unrelated subjects were positively correlated, which led him to postulate that a single general mental ability, or *g*, underlies and shapes human cognitive performance.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The initial development of common factor analysis with multiple factors was given by Louis Thurstone in two papers in the early 1930s, summarized in his 1935 book, *The Vector of Mind.* Thurstone introduced several important factor analysis concepts, including communality, uniqueness, and rotation.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] He advocated for "simple structure", and developed methods of rotation that could be used as a way to achieve such structure.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In Q methodology, William Stephenson, a student of Spearman, distinguish between *R* factor analysis, oriented toward the study of inter-individual differences, and *Q* factor analysis oriented toward subjective intra-individual differences.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Raymond Cattell was a strong advocate of factor analysis and psychometrics and used Thurstone's multi-factor theory to explain intelligence.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Cattell also developed the scree test and similarity coefficients.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis is used to identify "factors" that explain a variety of results on different tests.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] For example, intelligence research found that people who get a high score on a test of verbal ability are also good on other tests that require verbal abilities.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Researchers explained this by using factor analysis to isolate one factor, often called verbal intelligence, which represents the degree to which someone is able to solve problems involving verbal skills.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis in psychology is most often associated with intelligence research.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] However, it also has been used to find factors in a broad range of domains such as personality, attitudes, beliefs, etc.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] It is linked to psychometrics, as it can assess the validity of an instrument by finding if the instrument indeed measures the postulated factors.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis is a frequently used technique in cross-cultural research.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] It serves the purpose of extracting cultural dimensions.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The best known cultural dimensions models are those elaborated by Geert Hofstede, Ronald Inglehart, Christian Welzel, Shalom Schwartz and Michael Minkov.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] A popular visualization is Inglehart and Welzel's cultural map of the world.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In an early 1965 study, political systems around the world are examined via factor analysis to construct related theoretical models and research, compare political systems, and create typological categories.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] For these purposes, in this study seven basic political dimensions are identified, which are related to a wide variety of political behaviour: these dimensions are Access, Differentiation, Consensus, Sectionalism, Legitimation, Interest, and Leadership Theory and Research.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Other political scientists explore the measurement of internal political efficacy using four new questions added to the 1988 National Election Study.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis is here used to find that these items measure a single concept distinct from external efficacy and political trust, and that these four questions provided the best measure of internal political efficacy up to that point in time.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The data collection stage is usually done by marketing research professionals.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Survey questions ask the respondent to rate a product sample or descriptions of product concepts on a range of attributes.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Anywhere from five to twenty attributes are chosen.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] They could include things like: ease of use, weight, accuracy, durability, colourfulness, price, or size.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The attributes chosen will vary depending on the product being studied.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The same question is asked about all the products in the study.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The data for multiple products is coded and input into a statistical program such as R, SPSS, SAS, Stata, STATISTICA, JMP, and SYSTAT.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The analysis will isolate the underlying factors that explain the data using a matrix of associations.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis is an interdependence technique.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The complete set of interdependent relationships is examined.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] There is no specification of dependent variables, independent variables, or causality.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis assumes that all the rating data on different attributes can be reduced down to a few important dimensions.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] This reduction is possible because some attributes may be related to each other.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The rating given to any one attribute is partially the result of the influence of other attributes.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The statistical algorithm deconstructs the rating (called a raw score) into its various components and reconstructs the partial scores into underlying factor scores.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] The degree of correlation between the initial raw score and the final factor score is called a *factor loading*.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis has also been widely used in physical sciences such as geochemistry, hydrochemistry, astrophysics and cosmology, as well as biological sciences, such as ecology, molecular biology, neuroscience and biochemistry.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In groundwater quality management, it is important to relate the spatial distribution of different chemical parameters to different possible sources, which have different chemical signatures.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] For example, a sulfide mine is likely to be associated with high levels of acidity, dissolved sulfates and transition metals.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] These signatures can be identified as factors through R-mode factor analysis, and the location of possible sources can be suggested by contouring the factor scores.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In geochemistry, different factors can correspond to different mineral associations, and thus to mineralisation.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] Factor analysis can be used for summarizing high-density oligonucleotide DNA microarrays data at probe level for Affymetrix GeneChips.
[src:factor-analysis/factor-analysis] In this case, the latent variable corresponds to the RNA concentration in a sample.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable-model] A **latent variable model** is a statistical model that relates a set of observable variables (also called *manifest variables* or *indicators*) to a set of latent variables.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable-model] Latent variable models are applied across a wide range of fields such as biology, computer science, and social science.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable-model] It is assumed that the responses on the indicators or manifest variables are the result of an individual's position on the latent variable(s), and that the manifest variables have nothing in common after controlling for the latent variable (local independence).
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable-model] The Rasch model represents the simplest form of item response theory.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable-model] Mixture models are central to latent profile analysis.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable-model] In factor analysis and latent trait analysis the latent variables are treated as continuous normally distributed variables, and in latent profile analysis and latent class analysis as from a multinomial distribution.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable-model] The manifest variables in factor analysis and latent profile analysis are continuous and in most cases, their conditional distribution given the latent variables is assumed to be normal.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable-model] In latent trait analysis and latent class analysis, the manifest variables are discrete.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable-model] These variables could be dichotomous, ordinal or nominal variables.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable-model] Their conditional distributions are assumed to be binomial or multinomial.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] In statistics, **latent variables** (from Latin: present participle of *lateo* 'lie hidden') are variables that can only be inferred indirectly through a mathematical model from other **observable variables** that can be directly observed or measured.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] Latent variables may correspond to aspects of physical reality.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] These could in principle be measured, but may not be for practical reasons.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] In this situation, the term *hidden variables* is commonly used, reflecting the fact that the variables are meaningful, but not observable.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] Other latent variables correspond to abstract concepts, like categories, behavioral or mental states, or data structures.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] The terms *hypothetical variables* or *hypothetical constructs* may be used in these situations.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] The use of latent variables can serve to reduce the dimensionality of data.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] Many observable variables can be aggregated in a model to represent an underlying concept, making it easier to understand the data.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] In this sense, they serve a function similar to that of scientific theories.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] At the same time, latent variables link observable "sub-symbolic" data in the real world to symbolic data in the modeled world.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] Latent variables, as created by factor analytic methods, generally represent "shared" variance, or the degree to which variables "move" together.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] Variables that have no correlation cannot result in a latent construct based on the common factor model.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] Examples of latent variables from the field of economics include quality of life, business confidence, morale, happiness and conservatism: these are all variables which cannot be measured directly.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] However, by linking these latent variables to other, observable variables, the values of the latent variables can be inferred from measurements of the observable variables.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] Quality of life is a latent variable which cannot be measured directly, so observable variables are used to infer quality of life.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] Observable variables to measure quality of life include wealth, employment, environment, physical and mental health, education, recreation and leisure time, and social belonging.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] Latent-variable methodology is used in many branches of medicine.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] A class of problems that naturally lend themselves to latent variables approaches are longitudinal studies where the time scale (e.g. age of participant or time since study baseline) is not synchronized with the trait being studied.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] For such studies, an unobserved time scale that is synchronized with the trait being studied can be modeled as a transformation of the observed time scale using latent variables.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] Examples of this include disease progression modeling and modeling of growth (see box).
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] There exists a range of different model classes and methodology that make use of latent variables and allow inference in the presence of latent variables.
[src:factor-analysis/latent-variable] Bayesian statistics is often used for inferring latent variables.
[src:factor-analysis/varimax-rotation] In statistics, a **varimax rotation** is used to simplify the expression of a particular sub-space in terms of just a few major items each.
[src:factor-analysis/varimax-rotation] The actual coordinate system is unchanged, it is the orthogonal basis that is being rotated to align with those coordinates.
[src:factor-analysis/varimax-rotation] The sub-space found with principal component analysis or factor analysis is expressed as a dense basis with many non-zero weights which makes it hard to interpret.
[src:factor-analysis/varimax-rotation] Varimax is so called because it maximizes the sum of the variances of the squared loadings (squared correlations between variables and factors).
[src:factor-analysis/varimax-rotation] Preserving orthogonality requires that it is a rotation that leaves the sub-space invariant.
[src:factor-analysis/varimax-rotation] If these conditions hold, the factor loading matrix is said to have "simple structure," and varimax rotation brings the loading matrix closer to such simple structure (as much as the data allow).
[src:factor-analysis/varimax-rotation] From the perspective of individuals measured on the variables, varimax seeks a basis that most economically represents each individual—that is, each individual can be well described by a linear combination of only a few basis functions.
[src:factor-analysis/varimax-rotation] Suggested by Henry Felix Kaiser in 1958, it is a popular scheme for orthogonal rotation (where all factors remain uncorrelated with one another).
[src:factor-analysis/varimax-rotation] A summary of the use of varimax rotation and of other types of factor rotation is presented in this article on factor analysis.
